]]\n|[[Andy Schuttinger]]\n|[[Kimball Patterson]]\n|[[James W. McClelland]]\n|1:13.60\n|-\n|1917\n|[[Sun Briar]]\n|[[Willie Knapp]]\n|[[Henry McDaniel (racehorse trainer)|Henry McDaniel]]\n|[[Willis Sharpe Kilmer]]\n|1:15.60\n|-\n|1916\n|[[Campfire (horse)|Campfire]]\n|[[John McTaggart (jockey)|John McTaggart]]\n|[[T. J. Healey|Thomas J. Healey]]\n|[[Richard Thornton Wilson Jr.|Richard T. Wilson Jr.]]\n|1:14.60\n|-\n|1915\n|[[Dominant (horse)|Dominant]]\n|[[Joe Notter]]\n|[[James G. Rowe Sr.]]\n|[[Sunny Hill Plantation#Lewis S. Thompson|Lewis S. Thompson]]\n|1:13.80\n|-\n|1914\n|[[Regret (horse)|Regret]]\n|[[Joe Notter]]\n|[[James G. Rowe Sr.]]\n|[[Harry Payne Whitney]]\n|1:16.40\n|-\n|1913\n|[[Bringhurst (horse)|Bringhurst]]\n|[[Johnny Loftus]]\n|[[J. Oliver Keene]]\n|[[Johnson N. Camden Jr.]]\n|1:12.40\n|-\n|1910\n|[[Novelty (horse)|Novelty]]\n|[[A. Thomas]]\n|[[Sam Hildreth]]\n|[[Sam Hildreth]]\n|1:14.00\n|-\n|1909\n|[[Rocky O'Brien (horse)|Rocky O'Brien]]\n|[[Vincent Powers]]\n|Kimball Patterson\n|James MacManus\n|1:13.20\n|-\n|1908\n|[[Helmet (horse)|Helmet]]\n|[[Joe Notter]]\n|[[James G. Rowe Sr.]]\n|[[James R. Keene]]\n|1:12.20\n|-\n|1907\n|[[Jim Gaffney (horse)|Jim Gaffney]]\n|[[David Nicol]]\n|Frank D. Weir\n|[[Frank J. Farrell]]\n|1:15.00\n|-\n|1906\n|[[Peter Pan I|Peter Pan]]\n|[[Willie Knapp]]\n|[[James G. Rowe Sr.]]\n|[[James R. Keene]]\n|1:12.20\n|-\n|1905\n|[[Mohawk II]]\n|[[Arthur E. Redfern|Arthur Redfern]]\n|Hubert H. Hyner \n|[[John Sanford (1851)|John Sanford]]\n|1:13.40\n|-\n|1904\n|[[Tanya (horse)|Tanya]]\n|[[Gene Hildebrand]]\n|[[John W. Rogers (horse trainer)|John W. Rogers]]\n|[[Herman B. Duryea]]\n|1:13.20\n|-\n|1903\n|[[Delhi (horse)|Delhi]]\n|Willie Gannon\n|[[James G. Rowe Sr.]]\n|[[James R. Keene]]\n|1:13.20\n|}\n{{refbegin}}\n* Run in two divisions in 1974 and 1975.\n* In 1979, Rockhill Native finished first but was disqualified and placed sixth. \n* In 2000, there was a Dead Heat between Yonaguska and City Zip.\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9C0CE6D91230E132A25757C1A96E9C946597D6CF August 14, 1904 ''New York Times'' article on Tany's win in the inaugural Hopeful Stakes]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100117201119/http://ntra.com/races.aspx?section=races&id=30231 The 2008 Hopeful Stakes at the NTRA]\n* [http://helloracefans.com/races/ten-things/hopeful-stakes/ Ten Things You Should Know About the Hopeful Stakes]\n\n[[Category:1903 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Horse races in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Saratoga Race Course]]\n[[Category:Flat horse races for two-year-olds]]\n[[Category:Grade 1 stakes races in the United States]]\n[[Category:Graded stakes races in the United States]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1903]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the British horse race|Hopeful Stakes (Great Britain)}}\n{{for|the Japanese horse race|Hopeful Stakes (Japan)}}\n{{Infobox horseraces\n| class         = Grade I\n| horse race    = Hopeful Stakes\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| location      = [[Saratoga Race Course]]<br>[[Saratoga Springs, New York]], [[United States]]\n| inaugurated   = 1903\n| race type     = [[Thoroughbred]] - [[Flat racing]]\n| website       = https://www.nyra.com/saratoga/racing/stakes-schedule/hopeful/\n| distance      = 7 [[furlong]]s\n| surface       = Dirt\n| track         = left-handed\n| qualification = Two-year-olds\n| weight        = 120 lbs.\n| purse         = $350,000 (since 2014)<ref name=\"EquibaseProfile\">{{cite web|title=Hopeful Stakes Profile|url=http://www.equibase.com/profiles/Results.cfm?type=Stakes&stkid=1888|website=www.equibase.com|accessdate=6 September 2016}}</ref>\n| bonuses       = \n}}\nThe '''Hopeful Stakes''' is an American [[Thoroughbred horse race]] run annually at [[Saratoga Race Course]] in [[Saratoga Springs, New York]]. Open to two-year-old horses, the Hopeful is the first [[Graded stakes race|Grade I]] stakes for two-year-olds each season and historically has been a showcase for some of the top [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] horses at that age group. Raced on the dirt over a distance of seven [[furlong]]s, the [[Graded stakes race|Grade I]] event currently offers a purse of $350,000.\n\nInaugurated in 1903, the first edition was won by [[Delhi (horse)|Delhi]] who went on to win the 1904 [[Belmont Stakes]]. In 1904, the Hopeful Stakes was won by the [[filly]] [[Tanya (horse)|Tanya]].  She would go on to win the 1905 Belmont Stakes.\n\nInitially raced at a distance of six furlongs, from 1925 through 1993 it was run at six and a half furlongs and since 1994 at seven furlongs. Currently, the Hopeful Stakes is the first influential prep race leading up to the [[Breeders' Cup Juvenile]] and since 1925 has been a competition that marks the first time two-year-olds are tested at a distance beyond six furlongs. The name stems from the hope that every two-year-old handlers has for their horse's racing future.\n\nDue to the State of New York's legislated ban on [[parimutuel betting]], there was no race in 1911 and 1912. During [[World War II]], the Hopeful Stakes was run at [[Belmont Park]] in 1943, 1944, and 1945.\n\nOnly four horses have ever won all three Saratoga stakes events for two-year-olds. [[Regret (horse)|Regret]] (1914), [[Campfire (horse)|Campfire]] (1916), [[Dehere]] (1993), and [[City Zip]] (2000) each swept the Hopeful Stakes, [[Saratoga Special Stakes]], and the [[Sanford Stakes]].\n\nIn 2008, the race was sponsored by [[Three Chimneys Farm]] of [[Midway, Kentucky]].\n\n==Records==\n'''Time record:''' (at current 7 furlong distance)\n* 1:21.94 - [[Came Home]] (2001)\n\n'''Most wins by an owner:'''\n* 4 - [[George D. Widener Jr.]] (1928, 1950, 1961, 1966)\n\n'''Most wins by a [[jockey]]:'''\n* 6 - [[Jerry D. Bailey]] (1982, 1983, 1999, 2000, 2003, 2005)\n'''Most wins by trainer:'''\n* 8- [[D. Wayne Lukas]] (1990, 1991, 1995, 1999, 2000, 2009, 2013, 2017)\n\n==Winners of th